{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921224418,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_XwteKn6yrRx3IZMK2YBGH31M","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","offset":1,"limit":380},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n3: description: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n6:   - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n7:   - \"rust style guidance\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: implementation\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n14: \n15: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n20: \n21: ### Purpose\n22: \n23: Provides focused Rust guidance for rust/typescript interop — errors, parity & related resources in the OpenCode development environment.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use\n26: \n27: - Implementing or reviewing Rust code covered by this topic\n28: - Preserving TypeScript interoperability and deterministic behavior\n29: - Applying the corresponding Rust standards at an implementation boundary\n30: \n31: ## 2. ERROR STYLE\n32: \n33: Core public operations return domain-specific `Result` values backed by `thiserror`.\n34: \n35: ```rust\n36: use thiserror::Error;\n37: \n38: #[derive(Debug, Error)]\n39: pub enum RankingError {\n40:     #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n41:     EmptyIdentifier,\n42: \n43:     #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n44:     NonFiniteScore,\n45: \n46:     #[error(\"candidate limit {limit} exceeds maximum {maximum}\")]\n47:     LimitExceeded {\n48:         limit: u32,\n49:         maximum: u32,\n50:     },\n51: }\n52: ```\n53: \n54: Rules:\n55: \n56: - Core errors contain adapter-relevant structured context.\n57: - Core errors contain no napi-rs, WASM, or Node runtime types.\n58: - `anyhow` is prohibited in pure-core public APIs and exported functions.\n59: - `anyhow` MAY be used in sidecar `main`, build tooling, and the outermost non-ABI shell.\n60: - Every adapter owns one exhaustive mapping from core errors to stable JavaScript errors.\n61: - Error messages and codes covered by TypeScript contracts are golden-tested.\n62: - Panic only for an impossible internal invariant, never for recoverable boundary input.\n63: \n64: ## 3. EXHAUSTIVE ADAPTER ERROR MAPPING\n65: \n66: ```rust\n67: #[derive(Debug)]\n68: struct JsErrorShape {\n69:     code: &'static str,\n70:     message: String,\n71: }\n72: \n73: fn map_ranking_error(error: RankingError) -> JsErrorShape {\n74:     match error {\n75:         RankingError::EmptyIdentifier => JsErrorShape {\n76:             code: \"INVALID_IDENTIFIER\",\n77:             message: error.to_string(),\n78:         },\n79:         RankingError::NonFiniteScore => JsErrorShape {\n80:             code: \"NON_FINITE_SCORE\",\n81:             message: error.to_string(),\n82:         },\n83:         RankingError::LimitExceeded { .. } => JsErrorShape {\n84:             code: \"LIMIT_EXCEEDED\",\n85:             message: error.to_string(),\n86:         },\n87:     }\n88: }\n89: ```\n90: \n91: The adapter must also preserve whether the existing TypeScript operation throws synchronously or rejects a Promise.\n92: \n93: ## 4. PANIC-FREE BOUNDARY VALIDATION\n94: \n95: Do not use:\n96: \n97: ```rust\n98: let score = input.parse::<f64>().unwrap();\n99: let first = candidates[0].clone();\n100: let ordering = left.score.partial_cmp(&right.score).unwrap();\n101: ```\n102: \n103: Use typed failures:\n104: \n105: ```rust\n106: use std::num::ParseFloatError;\n107: \n108: fn parse_score(input: &str) -> Result<f64, ParseFloatError> {\n109:     input.parse::<f64>()\n110: }\n111: \n112: fn first_candidate(candidates: &[String]) -> Option<&str> {\n113:     candidates.first().map(String::as_str)\n114: }\n115: ```\n116: \n117: JavaScript-controlled data must not reach:\n118: \n119: - `unwrap`\n120: - `expect`\n121: - Unchecked indexing\n122: - `panic!`\n123: - `unreachable!`\n124: - Assertions used as validation\n125: - `partial_cmp(...).unwrap()`\n126: \n127: ## 5. DETERMINISTIC IDENTIFIERS\n128: \n129: Identifier generation preserves the exact TypeScript preimage contract:\n130: \n131: - Input fields\n132: - Field order\n133: - Separators\n134: - UTF-8 encoding\n135: - Hash algorithm\n136: - Lowercase hexadecimal encoding\n137: - Truncation length\n138: \n139: ```rust\n140: use sha2::{Digest, Sha256};\n141: \n142: fn deterministic_id(namespace: &str, name: &str) -> String {\n143:     let preimage = format!(\"{namespace}\\0{name}\");\n144:     let digest = Sha256::digest(preimage.as_bytes());\n145:     let hexadecimal = format!(\"{digest:x}\");\n146:     hexadecimal[..24].to_owned()\n147: }\n148: ```\n149: \n150: This example is correct only if the TypeScript oracle uses the same fields, NUL delimiter, UTF-8 bytes, SHA-256, lowercase hexadecimal output, and 24-character truncation. Never infer those details from a semantically similar implementation.\n151: \n152: ## 6. STABLE SERIALIZATION\n153: \n154: Do not assume `serde_json` reproduces JavaScript byte output automatically.\n155: \n156: Potential differences include:\n157: \n158: - Number spelling\n159: - Negative zero\n160: - Exponent notation\n161: - Omitted versus `null` fields\n162: - Escaping\n163: - Key order\n164: - Non-finite values\n165: - Map iteration order\n166: \n167: Use passive DTOs and canonical maps:\n168: \n169: ```rust\n170: use std::collections::BTreeMap;\n171: \n172: use serde::Serialize;\n173: \n174: #[derive(Debug, Serialize)]\n175: #[serde(rename_all = \"camelCase\")]\n176: struct SearchResponse {\n177:     results: Vec<SearchResult>,\n178:     metadata: BTreeMap<String, String>,\n179: }\n180: \n181: #[derive(Debug, Serialize)]\n182: struct SearchResult {\n183:     id: String,\n184:     score: f64,\n185: }\n186: ```\n187: \n188: Byte-for-byte fixtures remain required even when the Rust structure appears equivalent to the TypeScript object.\n189: \n190: ## 7. ASYNC AND THREADING\n191: \n192: Keep parsing, scoring, ranking, hashing, canonicalization, and serialization preparation synchronous in the core.\n193: \n194: Use napi-rs `AsyncTask` only for measured CPU or blocking work that would materially block Node.\n195: \n196: Before worker execution:\n197: \n198: - Convert JavaScript values into owned DTOs.\n199: - Copy JavaScript-owned buffers.\n200: - Validate cheap structural constraints.\n201: - Do not retain `Env`, `JsValue`, or thread-affine handles.\n202: \n203: After worker execution:\n204: \n205: - Reorder results by deterministic sequence keys.\n206: - Canonicalize output synchronously.\n207: - Map typed errors on the JavaScript thread.\n208: \n209: Use Tokio only for genuine Rust-owned asynchronous I/O. Use Rayon only after benchmark evidence demonstrates a useful batch-size threshold.\n210: \n211: Parity-visible floating-point reductions MUST NOT run in nondeterministic parallel order. If parallel reduction is unavoidable, fix the reduction tree and golden-test it across every supported target.\n212: \n213: Baseline WASM is single-threaded. Promise bridging does not create CPU parallelism.\n214: \n215: ## 8. NAPI-RS EXPORT EXAMPLE\n216: \n217: ```rust\n218: use napi::bindgen_prelude::{Error, Status};\n219: use napi_derive::napi;\n220: \n221: #[napi(object)]\n222: pub struct CandidateDto {\n223:     pub id: String,\n224:     pub score: f64,\n225: }\n226: \n227: #[napi(js_name = \"rankCandidates\")]\n228: pub fn rank_candidates(candidates: Vec<CandidateDto>) -> napi::Result<Vec<CandidateDto>> {\n229:     let mut candidates = candidates;\n230: \n231:     if candidates.iter().any(|candidate| !candidate.score.is_finite()) {\n232:         return Err(Error::new(\n233:             Status::InvalidArg,\n234:             \"NON_FINITE_SCORE: candidate score must be finite\",\n235:         ));\n236:     }\n237: \n238:     candidates.sort_by(|left, right| {\n239:         right\n240:             .score\n241:             .total_cmp(&left.score)\n242:             .then_with(|| left.id.cmp(&right.id))\n243:     });\n244: \n245:     Ok(candidates)\n246: }\n247: ```\n248: \n249: In production, ranking belongs in the pure core and the adapter converts DTOs and errors only. The example shows the JavaScript-visible naming and owned boundary shape.\n250: \n251: ## 9. WASM-BINDGEN EXPORT EXAMPLE\n252: \n253: ```rust\n254: use wasm_bindgen::prelude::*;\n255: \n256: #[wasm_bindgen(js_name = normalizeScore)]\n257: pub fn normalize_score(value: f64) -> Result<f64, JsValue> {\n258:     if !value.is_finite() {\n259:         return Err(JsValue::from_str(\n260:             \"NON_FINITE_SCORE: score must be finite\",\n261:         ));\n262:     }\n263: \n264:     let normalized = (value * 1_000_000.0).round() / 1_000_000.0;\n265:     Ok(if normalized == 0.0 { 0.0 } else { normalized })\n266: }\n267: ```\n268: \n269: The exact rounding implementation and error shape require differential fixtures against the TypeScript oracle before release.\n270: \n271: ## 10. COEXISTENCE AND FALLBACKS\n272: \n273: TypeScript retains fallback selection. Rust adapters expose capability; they do not silently choose themselves.\n274: \n275: ```typescript\n276: const result = flags.nativeRanking && nativeAddon !== null\n277:   ? await nativeAddon.rankCandidates(input)\n278:   : await rankCandidatesTypeScript(input);\n279: ```\n280: \n281: Both paths must emit identical bytes for the supported input domain. A semantic deep-equality test is useful for diagnosis but does not replace the byte comparison.\n282: \n283: ## 11. DIFFERENTIAL TEST CONTRACT\n284: \n285: The release-level assertion is:\n286: \n287: ```rust\n288: fn assert_byte_parity(\n289:     typescript_bytes: &[u8],\n290:     rust_bytes: &[u8],\n291: ) {\n292:     assert_eq!(typescript_bytes, rust_bytes);\n293: }\n294: ```\n295: \n296: Golden fixtures MUST originate from the pinned TypeScript oracle. Rust must not author or automatically accept its own expected output.\n297: \n298: Parity fixtures cover:\n299: \n300: - Six-decimal edge cases\n301: - Positive and negative halfway values\n302: - Negative zero\n303: - Very small and very large finite numbers\n304: - Complete sorting ties\n305: - Identifier alphabet boundaries\n306: - Unicode and UTF-8 preimages\n307: - Optional and omitted fields\n308: - Empty collections\n309: - Map and object ordering\n310: - Error codes and exact messages\n311: - Synchronous throws and Promise rejections\n312: - Native and WASM artifacts\n313: \n314: ## 12. RELATED RESOURCES\n315: \n316: - [quality_standards.md](../quality_standards/overview_and_data_ownership.md) - Ownership, safety, ABI contracts, error translation, concurrency, Cargo, and parity gates\n317: - [quick_reference.md](../quick_reference/overview_and_boundary_template.md) - Copy-paste Rust boundary templates, deterministic recipes, and build commands\n\n(End of file - total 317 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n  - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","text":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n  - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvides focused Rust guidance for rust/typescript interop — errors, parity & related resources in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Implementing or reviewing Rust code covered by this topic\n- Preserving TypeScript interoperability and deterministic behavior\n- Applying the corresponding Rust standards at an implementation boundary\n\n## 2. ERROR STYLE\n\nCore public operations return domain-specific `Result` values backed by `thiserror`.\n\n```rust\nuse thiserror::Error;\n\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\npub enum RankingError {\n    #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n    EmptyIdentifier,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n    NonFiniteScore,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate limit {limit} exceeds maximum {maximum}\")]\n    LimitExceeded {\n        limit: u32,\n        maximum: u32,\n    },\n}\n```\n\nRules:\n\n- Core errors contain adapter-relevant structured context.\n- Core errors contain no napi-rs, WASM, or Node runtime types.\n- `anyhow` is prohibited in pure-core public APIs and exported functions.\n- `anyhow` MAY be used in sidecar `main`, build tooling, and the outermost non-ABI shell.\n- Every adapter owns one exhaustive mapping from core errors to stable JavaScript errors.\n- Error messages and codes covered by TypeScript contracts are golden-tested.\n- Panic only for an impossible internal invariant, never for recoverable boundary input.\n\n## 3. EXHAUSTIVE ADAPTER ERROR MAPPING\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct JsErrorShape {\n    code: &'static str,\n    message: String,\n}\n\nfn map_ranking_error(error: RankingError) -> JsErrorShape {\n    match error {\n        RankingError::EmptyIdentifier => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"INVALID_IDENTIFIER\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n        RankingError::NonFiniteScore => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"NON_FINITE_SCORE\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n        RankingError::LimitExceeded { .. } => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"LIMIT_EXCEEDED\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe adapter must also preserve whether the existing TypeScript operation throws synchronously or rejects a Promise.\n\n## 4. PANIC-FREE BOUNDARY VALIDATION\n\nDo not use:\n\n```rust\nlet score = input.parse::<f64>().unwrap();\nlet first = candidates[0].clone();\nlet ordering = left.score.partial_cmp(&right.score).unwrap();\n```\n\nUse typed failures:\n\n```rust\nuse std::num::ParseFloatError;\n\nfn parse_score(input: &str) -> Result<f64, ParseFloatError> {\n    input.parse::<f64>()\n}\n\nfn first_candidate(candidates: &[String]) -> Option<&str> {\n    candidates.first().map(String::as_str)\n}\n```\n\nJavaScript-controlled data must not reach:\n\n- `unwrap`\n- `expect`\n- Unchecked indexing\n- `panic!`\n- `unreachable!`\n- Assertions used as validation\n- `partial_cmp(...).unwrap()`\n\n## 5. DETERMINISTIC IDENTIFIERS\n\nIdentifier generation preserves the exact TypeScript preimage contract:\n\n- Input fields\n- Field order\n- Separators\n- UTF-8 encoding\n- Hash algorithm\n- Lowercase hexadecimal encoding\n- Truncation length\n\n```rust\nuse sha2::{Digest, Sha256};\n\nfn deterministic_id(namespace: &str, name: &str) -> String {\n    let preimage = format!(\"{namespace}\\0{name}\");\n    let digest = Sha256::digest(preimage.as_bytes());\n    let hexadecimal = format!(\"{digest:x}\");\n    hexadecimal[..24].to_owned()\n}\n```\n\nThis example is correct only if the TypeScript oracle uses the same fields, NUL delimiter, UTF-8 bytes, SHA-256, lowercase hexadecimal output, and 24-character truncation. Never infer those details from a semantically similar implementation.\n\n## 6. STABLE SERIALIZATION\n\nDo not assume `serde_json` reproduces JavaScript byte output automatically.\n\nPotential differences include:\n\n- Number spelling\n- Negative zero\n- Exponent notation\n- Omitted versus `null` fields\n- Escaping\n- Key order\n- Non-finite values\n- Map iteration order\n\nUse passive DTOs and canonical maps:\n\n```rust\nuse std::collections::BTreeMap;\n\nuse serde::Serialize;\n\n#[derive(Debug, Serialize)]\n#[serde(rename_all = \"camelCase\")]\nstruct SearchResponse {\n    results: Vec<SearchResult>,\n    metadata: BTreeMap<String, String>,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Serialize)]\nstruct SearchResult {\n    id: String,\n    score: f64,\n}\n```\n\nByte-for-byte fixtures remain required even when the Rust structure appears equivalent to the TypeScript object.\n\n## 7. ASYNC AND THREADING\n\nKeep parsing, scoring, ranking, hashing, canonicalization, and serialization preparation synchronous in the core.\n\nUse napi-rs `AsyncTask` only for measured CPU or blocking work that would materially block Node.\n\nBefore worker execution:\n\n- Convert JavaScript values into owned DTOs.\n- Copy JavaScript-owned buffers.\n- Validate cheap structural constraints.\n- Do not retain `Env`, `JsValue`, or thread-affine handles.\n\nAfter worker execution:\n\n- Reorder results by deterministic sequence keys.\n- Canonicalize output synchronously.\n- Map typed errors on the JavaScript thread.\n\nUse Tokio only for genuine Rust-owned asynchronous I/O. Use Rayon only after benchmark evidence demonstrates a useful batch-size threshold.\n\nParity-visible floating-point reductions MUST NOT run in nondeterministic parallel order. If parallel reduction is unavoidable, fix the reduction tree and golden-test it across every supported target.\n\nBaseline WASM is single-threaded. Promise bridging does not create CPU parallelism.\n\n## 8. NAPI-RS EXPORT EXAMPLE\n\n```rust\nuse napi::bindgen_prelude::{Error, Status};\nuse napi_derive::napi;\n\n#[napi(object)]\npub struct CandidateDto {\n    pub id: String,\n    pub score: f64,\n}\n\n#[napi(js_name = \"rankCandidates\")]\npub fn rank_candidates(candidates: Vec<CandidateDto>) -> napi::Result<Vec<CandidateDto>> {\n    let mut candidates = candidates;\n\n    if candidates.iter().any(|candidate| !candidate.score.is_finite()) {\n        return Err(Error::new(\n            Status::InvalidArg,\n            \"NON_FINITE_SCORE: candidate score must be finite\",\n        ));\n    }\n\n    candidates.sort_by(|left, right| {\n        right\n            .score\n            .total_cmp(&left.score)\n            .then_with(|| left.id.cmp(&right.id))\n    });\n\n    Ok(candidates)\n}\n```\n\nIn production, ranking belongs in the pure core and the adapter converts DTOs and errors only. The example shows the JavaScript-visible naming and owned boundary shape.\n\n## 9. WASM-BINDGEN EXPORT EXAMPLE\n\n```rust\nuse wasm_bindgen::prelude::*;\n\n#[wasm_bindgen(js_name = normalizeScore)]\npub fn normalize_score(value: f64) -> Result<f64, JsValue> {\n    if !value.is_finite() {\n        return Err(JsValue::from_str(\n            \"NON_FINITE_SCORE: score must be finite\",\n        ));\n    }\n\n    let normalized = (value * 1_000_000.0).round() / 1_000_000.0;\n    Ok(if normalized == 0.0 { 0.0 } else { normalized })\n}\n```\n\nThe exact rounding implementation and error shape require differential fixtures against the TypeScript oracle before release.\n\n## 10. COEXISTENCE AND FALLBACKS\n\nTypeScript retains fallback selection. Rust adapters expose capability; they do not silently choose themselves.\n\n```typescript\nconst result = flags.nativeRanking && nativeAddon !== null\n  ? await nativeAddon.rankCandidates(input)\n  : await rankCandidatesTypeScript(input);\n```\n\nBoth paths must emit identical bytes for the supported input domain. A semantic deep-equality test is useful for diagnosis but does not replace the byte comparison.\n\n## 11. DIFFERENTIAL TEST CONTRACT\n\nThe release-level assertion is:\n\n```rust\nfn assert_byte_parity(\n    typescript_bytes: &[u8],\n    rust_bytes: &[u8],\n) {\n    assert_eq!(typescript_bytes, rust_bytes);\n}\n```\n\nGolden fixtures MUST originate from the pinned TypeScript oracle. Rust must not author or automatically accept its own expected output.\n\nParity fixtures cover:\n\n- Six-decimal edge cases\n- Positive and negative halfway values\n- Negative zero\n- Very small and very large finite numbers\n- Complete sorting ties\n- Identifier alphabet boundaries\n- Unicode and UTF-8 preimages\n- Optional and omitted fields\n- Empty collections\n- Map and object ordering\n- Error codes and exact messages\n- Synchronous throws and Promise rejections\n- Native and WASM artifacts\n\n## 12. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [quality_standards.md](../quality_standards/overview_and_data_ownership.md) - Ownership, safety, ABI contracts, error translation, concurrency, Cargo, and parity gates\n- [quick_reference.md](../quick_reference/overview_and_boundary_template.md) - Copy-paste Rust boundary templates, deterministic recipes, and build commands","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":317,"totalLines":317,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","time":{"start":1783921224406,"end":1783921224416}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eb181f2c4bf2054016a547a4825708191ab431d8cfbe32a3a"}},"id":"prt_f59fdaa34001chicC0JAI3tcQu","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f59fd3cf1001i0c3uxYZV1prra"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921224479,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_L0jYlcVMI9pLlg8bHhKFDAlB","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/security_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md","offset":1,"limit":330},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/security_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Security Patterns - OWASP Top 10 Integration\n3: description: Security hardening patterns covering XSS prevention, CSRF protection, and input validation.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow security patterns\"\n6:   - \"xss prevention frontend\"\n7:   - \"csrf protection checklist\"\n8:   - \"owasp top ten frontend\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.3\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Security Patterns - OWASP Top 10 Integration\n15: \n16: Security hardening patterns covering XSS prevention, CSRF protection, and input validation.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: Frontend security checklist based on OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities, covering input validation, injection prevention, and secure data handling.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use\n26: Apply during Phase 1 (Implementation) when:\n27: - Handling user input (forms, search, etc.)\n28: - Making API calls\n29: - Displaying user-generated content\n30: - Storing data (localStorage, sessionStorage, cookies)\n31: - Before deploying to production\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. SECURITY CHECKLIST\n36: \n37: ### Input Validation & XSS Prevention\n38: \n39: **Sanitize User Input:**\n40: ```javascript\n41: // ✅ GOOD: Sanitize before display\n42: function sanitize_html(str) {\n43:   const div = document.createElement('div');\n44:   div.textContent = str;  // Automatically escapes HTML\n45:   return div.innerHTML;\n46: }\n47: \n48: const user_input = '<script>alert(\"XSS\")</script>';\n49: element.innerHTML = sanitize_html(user_input);\n50: // Result: &lt;script&gt;alert(\"XSS\")&lt;/script&gt;\n51: \n52: // ❌ BAD: Direct innerHTML without sanitization\n53: element.innerHTML = user_input;  // XSS vulnerability!\n54: ```\n55: \n56: **Use textContent When Possible:**\n57: ```javascript\n58: // ✅ GOOD: Use textContent for plain text\n59: element.textContent = user_input;  // Safe, no HTML rendering\n60: \n61: // ❌ BAD: innerHTML for plain text\n62: element.innerHTML = user_input;  // Unnecessary risk\n63: ```\n64: \n65: **Validate Input Format:**\n66: ```javascript\n67: // ✅ GOOD: Validate email format\n68: function is_valid_email(email) {\n69:   const email_regex = /^[^\\s@]+@[^\\s@]+\\.[^\\s@]+$/;\n70:   return email_regex.test(email);\n71: }\n72: \n73: if (!is_valid_email(user_email)) {\n74:   throw new Error('Invalid email format');\n75: }\n76: \n77: // ❌ BAD: Accept any input\n78: const user_email = input.value;  // No validation\n79: send_to_api(user_email);\n80: ```\n81: \n82: **Checklist:**\n83: - [ ] All user input sanitized before display\n84: - [ ] textContent used instead of innerHTML when possible\n85: - [ ] HTML entities escaped in user-generated content\n86: - [ ] Input format validated (email, phone, URL, etc.)\n87: - [ ] No eval() or Function() constructor with user input\n88: \n89: ### CSRF Protection\n90: \n91: **SameSite Cookies:**\n92: ```javascript\n93: // ✅ GOOD: Set SameSite on a non-sensitive, client-set cookie (e.g. a UI preference)\n94: document.cookie = \"ui_theme=dark; SameSite=Strict; Secure; Path=/\";\n95: \n96: // ❌ BAD: No SameSite attribute\n97: document.cookie = \"ui_theme=dark\";  // Sent on cross-site requests\n98: ```\n99: \n100: > Session tokens must NOT be set via `document.cookie` — a JavaScript-set cookie cannot be `HttpOnly`, so it is readable by XSS. Session cookies belong in a server-set `Set-Cookie: … Secure; HttpOnly; SameSite=Strict` header (see the Sensitive Data Storage section). Use client-set cookies only for non-sensitive values.\n101: \n102: **CSRF Tokens:**\n103: ```html\n104: <!-- ✅ GOOD: Include CSRF token in forms -->\n105: <form method=\"POST\">\n106:   <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"csrf_token\" value=\"${csrfToken}\">\n107:   <input type=\"text\" name=\"username\">\n108:   <button type=\"submit\">Submit</button>\n109: </form>\n110: \n111: <!-- Server-side verification required -->\n112: ```\n113: \n114: **Verify Origin/Referer:**\n115: ```javascript\n116: // ✅ GOOD: Verify request origin (server-side)\n117: const allowed_origins = ['https://example.com'];\n118: if (!allowed_origins.includes(req.headers.origin)) {\n119:   throw new Error('Invalid origin');\n120: }\n121: ```\n122: \n123: **Checklist:**\n124: - [ ] SameSite=Strict set on cookies\n125: - [ ] CSRF tokens implemented for state-changing operations\n126: - [ ] Origin/Referer headers verified (server-side)\n127: - [ ] GET requests never modify state\n128: \n129: ### Injection Prevention\n130: \n131: **SQL/NoSQL Injection:**\n132: ```javascript\n133: // ✅ GOOD: Parameterized queries (server-side)\n134: const query = 'SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ?';\n135: db.execute(query, [user_email]);\n136: \n137: // ❌ BAD: String concatenation\n138: const query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '${user_email}'`;\n139: // Vulnerable to SQL injection!\n140: ```\n141: \n142: **Command Injection:**\n143: ```javascript\n144: // ✅ GOOD: Validate and sanitize inputs\n145: const allowed_commands = ['start', 'stop', 'restart'];\n146: if (!allowed_commands.includes(user_command)) {\n147:   throw new Error('Invalid command');\n148: }\n149: \n150: // ❌ BAD: Execute user input directly\n151: exec(user_command);  // Command injection vulnerability!\n152: ```\n153: \n154: **Never Execute User Input:**\n155: ```javascript\n156: // ❌ BAD: eval() with user input\n157: eval(user_input);  // Extreme vulnerability\n158: \n159: // ❌ BAD: Function constructor\n160: new Function(user_input)();  // Also vulnerable\n161: \n162: // ❌ BAD: setTimeout/setInterval with strings\n163: setTimeout(user_input, 1000);  // Vulnerable\n164: ```\n165: \n166: **Checklist:**\n167: - [ ] Parameterized queries used (no string concatenation)\n168: - [ ] All inputs validated and sanitized\n169: - [ ] Never use eval(), Function(), or execute user input\n170: - [ ] Whitelist approach for allowed values\n171: \n172: ### Security Headers\n173: \n174: **Content Security Policy (CSP):**\n175: ```html\n176: <!-- ✅ GOOD: Strict CSP -->\n177: <meta http-equiv=\"Content-Security-Policy\"\n178:       content=\"default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' https://cdn.jsdelivr.net; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'\">\n179: \n180: <!-- ❌ BAD: No CSP or overly permissive -->\n181: <meta http-equiv=\"Content-Security-Policy\" content=\"default-src *\">\n182: ```\n183: \n184: **Other Security Headers:**\n185: ```html\n186: <!-- X-Content-Type-Options -->\n187: <meta http-equiv=\"X-Content-Type-Options\" content=\"nosniff\">\n188: \n189: <!-- X-Frame-Options -->\n190: <meta http-equiv=\"X-Frame-Options\" content=\"DENY\">\n191: \n192: <!-- Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) - server-side -->\n193: Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains\n194: ```\n195: \n196: **Checklist:**\n197: - [ ] Content-Security-Policy set (restrict script/style sources)\n198: - [ ] X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff set\n199: - [ ] X-Frame-Options: DENY or SAMEORIGIN set\n200: - [ ] Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) enabled (server-side)\n201: - [ ] Referrer-Policy configured appropriately\n202: \n203: ### Access Control\n204: \n205: **Client-Side Authorization (UI Only):**\n206: ```javascript\n207: // ⚠️ WARNING: Client-side checks are for UX only, NOT security\n208: // Always verify on server-side\n209: \n210: // ✅ GOOD: Hide UI elements, verify on backend\n211: if (user.role === 'admin') {\n212:   adminPanel.style.display = 'block';  // UI only\n213: }\n214: // Server MUST verify user.role before serving admin data\n215: \n216: // ❌ BAD: Client-side only authorization\n217: if (user.role === 'admin') {\n218:   fetchAdminData();  // Vulnerable if server doesn't verify\n219: }\n220: ```\n221: \n222: **Least Privilege Principle:**\n223: ```javascript\n224: // ✅ GOOD: Request only necessary permissions\n225: const data = await fetch('/api/user/profile');  // Specific endpoint\n226: \n227: // ❌ BAD: Request more than needed\n228: const data = await fetch('/api/admin/all-users');  // Excessive permissions\n229: ```\n230: \n231: **Checklist:**\n232: - [ ] User authorization verified on EVERY server request\n233: - [ ] Least privilege principle implemented\n234: - [ ] Never trust client-side authorization checks\n235: - [ ] Sensitive operations require re-authentication\n236: \n237: ### Data Storage Security\n238: \n239: **localStorage/sessionStorage:**\n240: ```javascript\n241: // ✅ GOOD: Never store sensitive data in localStorage\n242: sessionStorage.setItem('theme', 'dark');  // Non-sensitive data OK\n243: \n244: // ❌ BAD: Store sensitive data\n245: localStorage.setItem('password', user_password);  // Vulnerable to XSS\n246: localStorage.setItem('token', auth_token);  // Accessible to all scripts\n247: ```\n248: \n249: **Cookies:**\n250: ```javascript\n251: // ✅ GOOD: Secure, HttpOnly cookies (server-side)\n252: Set-Cookie: session=abc123; Secure; HttpOnly; SameSite=Strict\n253: \n254: // ❌ BAD: JavaScript-accessible cookies with sensitive data\n255: document.cookie = \"session=abc123\";  // Accessible to XSS\n256: ```\n257: \n258: **Checklist:**\n259: - [ ] No sensitive data in localStorage/sessionStorage\n260: - [ ] Cookies set with Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite attributes\n261: - [ ] Sensitive data encrypted if stored client-side\n262: - [ ] Clear storage on logout\n263: \n264: ---\n265: \n\n(End of file - total 265 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Security Patterns - OWASP Top 10 Integration\ndescription: Security hardening patterns covering XSS prevention, CSRF protection, and input validation.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow security patterns\"\n  - \"xss prevention frontend\"\n  - \"csrf protection checklist\"\n  - \"owasp top ten frontend\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.3\n---\n\n# Security Patterns - OWASP Top 10 Integration\n\nSecurity hardening patterns covering XSS prevention, CSRF protection, and input validation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/security_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md","text":"---\ntitle: Security Patterns - OWASP Top 10 Integration\ndescription: Security hardening patterns covering XSS prevention, CSRF protection, and input validation.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow security patterns\"\n  - \"xss prevention frontend\"\n  - \"csrf protection checklist\"\n  - \"owasp top ten frontend\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.3\n---\n\n# Security Patterns - OWASP Top 10 Integration\n\nSecurity hardening patterns covering XSS prevention, CSRF protection, and input validation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nFrontend security checklist based on OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities, covering input validation, injection prevention, and secure data handling.\n\n### When to Use\nApply during Phase 1 (Implementation) when:\n- Handling user input (forms, search, etc.)\n- Making API calls\n- Displaying user-generated content\n- Storing data (localStorage, sessionStorage, cookies)\n- Before deploying to production\n\n---\n\n## 2. SECURITY CHECKLIST\n\n### Input Validation & XSS Prevention\n\n**Sanitize User Input:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Sanitize before display\nfunction sanitize_html(str) {\n  const div = document.createElement('div');\n  div.textContent = str;  // Automatically escapes HTML\n  return div.innerHTML;\n}\n\nconst user_input = '<script>alert(\"XSS\")</script>';\nelement.innerHTML = sanitize_html(user_input);\n// Result: &lt;script&gt;alert(\"XSS\")&lt;/script&gt;\n\n// ❌ BAD: Direct innerHTML without sanitization\nelement.innerHTML = user_input;  // XSS vulnerability!\n```\n\n**Use textContent When Possible:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Use textContent for plain text\nelement.textContent = user_input;  // Safe, no HTML rendering\n\n// ❌ BAD: innerHTML for plain text\nelement.innerHTML = user_input;  // Unnecessary risk\n```\n\n**Validate Input Format:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Validate email format\nfunction is_valid_email(email) {\n  const email_regex = /^[^\\s@]+@[^\\s@]+\\.[^\\s@]+$/;\n  return email_regex.test(email);\n}\n\nif (!is_valid_email(user_email)) {\n  throw new Error('Invalid email format');\n}\n\n// ❌ BAD: Accept any input\nconst user_email = input.value;  // No validation\nsend_to_api(user_email);\n```\n\n**Checklist:**\n- [ ] All user input sanitized before display\n- [ ] textContent used instead of innerHTML when possible\n- [ ] HTML entities escaped in user-generated content\n- [ ] Input format validated (email, phone, URL, etc.)\n- [ ] No eval() or Function() constructor with user input\n\n### CSRF Protection\n\n**SameSite Cookies:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Set SameSite on a non-sensitive, client-set cookie (e.g. a UI preference)\ndocument.cookie = \"ui_theme=dark; SameSite=Strict; Secure; Path=/\";\n\n// ❌ BAD: No SameSite attribute\ndocument.cookie = \"ui_theme=dark\";  // Sent on cross-site requests\n```\n\n> Session tokens must NOT be set via `document.cookie` — a JavaScript-set cookie cannot be `HttpOnly`, so it is readable by XSS. Session cookies belong in a server-set `Set-Cookie: … Secure; HttpOnly; SameSite=Strict` header (see the Sensitive Data Storage section). Use client-set cookies only for non-sensitive values.\n\n**CSRF Tokens:**\n```html\n<!-- ✅ GOOD: Include CSRF token in forms -->\n<form method=\"POST\">\n  <input type=\"hidden\" name=\"csrf_token\" value=\"${csrfToken}\">\n  <input type=\"text\" name=\"username\">\n  <button type=\"submit\">Submit</button>\n</form>\n\n<!-- Server-side verification required -->\n```\n\n**Verify Origin/Referer:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Verify request origin (server-side)\nconst allowed_origins = ['https://example.com'];\nif (!allowed_origins.includes(req.headers.origin)) {\n  throw new Error('Invalid origin');\n}\n```\n\n**Checklist:**\n- [ ] SameSite=Strict set on cookies\n- [ ] CSRF tokens implemented for state-changing operations\n- [ ] Origin/Referer headers verified (server-side)\n- [ ] GET requests never modify state\n\n### Injection Prevention\n\n**SQL/NoSQL Injection:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Parameterized queries (server-side)\nconst query = 'SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ?';\ndb.execute(query, [user_email]);\n\n// ❌ BAD: String concatenation\nconst query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '${user_email}'`;\n// Vulnerable to SQL injection!\n```\n\n**Command Injection:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Validate and sanitize inputs\nconst allowed_commands = ['start', 'stop', 'restart'];\nif (!allowed_commands.includes(user_command)) {\n  throw new Error('Invalid command');\n}\n\n// ❌ BAD: Execute user input directly\nexec(user_command);  // Command injection vulnerability!\n```\n\n**Never Execute User Input:**\n```javascript\n// ❌ BAD: eval() with user input\neval(user_input);  // Extreme vulnerability\n\n// ❌ BAD: Function constructor\nnew Function(user_input)();  // Also vulnerable\n\n// ❌ BAD: setTimeout/setInterval with strings\nsetTimeout(user_input, 1000);  // Vulnerable\n```\n\n**Checklist:**\n- [ ] Parameterized queries used (no string concatenation)\n- [ ] All inputs validated and sanitized\n- [ ] Never use eval(), Function(), or execute user input\n- [ ] Whitelist approach for allowed values\n\n### Security Headers\n\n**Content Security Policy (CSP):**\n```html\n<!-- ✅ GOOD: Strict CSP -->\n<meta http-equiv=\"Content-Security-Policy\"\n      content=\"default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' https://cdn.jsdelivr.net; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'\">\n\n<!-- ❌ BAD: No CSP or overly permissive -->\n<meta http-equiv=\"Content-Security-Policy\" content=\"default-src *\">\n```\n\n**Other Security Headers:**\n```html\n<!-- X-Content-Type-Options -->\n<meta http-equiv=\"X-Content-Type-Options\" content=\"nosniff\">\n\n<!-- X-Frame-Options -->\n<meta http-equiv=\"X-Frame-Options\" content=\"DENY\">\n\n<!-- Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) - server-side -->\nStrict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains\n```\n\n**Checklist:**\n- [ ] Content-Security-Policy set (restrict script/style sources)\n- [ ] X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff set\n- [ ] X-Frame-Options: DENY or SAMEORIGIN set\n- [ ] Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) enabled (server-side)\n- [ ] Referrer-Policy configured appropriately\n\n### Access Control\n\n**Client-Side Authorization (UI Only):**\n```javascript\n// ⚠️ WARNING: Client-side checks are for UX only, NOT security\n// Always verify on server-side\n\n// ✅ GOOD: Hide UI elements, verify on backend\nif (user.role === 'admin') {\n  adminPanel.style.display = 'block';  // UI only\n}\n// Server MUST verify user.role before serving admin data\n\n// ❌ BAD: Client-side only authorization\nif (user.role === 'admin') {\n  fetchAdminData();  // Vulnerable if server doesn't verify\n}\n```\n\n**Least Privilege Principle:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Request only necessary permissions\nconst data = await fetch('/api/user/profile');  // Specific endpoint\n\n// ❌ BAD: Request more than needed\nconst data = await fetch('/api/admin/all-users');  // Excessive permissions\n```\n\n**Checklist:**\n- [ ] User authorization verified on EVERY server request\n- [ ] Least privilege principle implemented\n- [ ] Never trust client-side authorization checks\n- [ ] Sensitive operations require re-authentication\n\n### Data Storage Security\n\n**localStorage/sessionStorage:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Never store sensitive data in localStorage\nsessionStorage.setItem('theme', 'dark');  // Non-sensitive data OK\n\n// ❌ BAD: Store sensitive data\nlocalStorage.setItem('password', user_password);  // Vulnerable to XSS\nlocalStorage.setItem('token', auth_token);  // Accessible to all scripts\n```\n\n**Cookies:**\n```javascript\n// ✅ GOOD: Secure, HttpOnly cookies (server-side)\nSet-Cookie: session=abc123; Secure; HttpOnly; SameSite=Strict\n\n// ❌ BAD: JavaScript-accessible cookies with sensitive data\ndocument.cookie = \"session=abc123\";  // Accessible to XSS\n```\n\n**Checklist:**\n- [ ] No sensitive data in localStorage/sessionStorage\n- [ ] Cookies set with Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite attributes\n- [ ] Sensitive data encrypted if stored client-side\n- [ ] Clear storage on logout\n\n---\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":265,"totalLines":265,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/security_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md","time":{"start":1783921224465,"end":1783921224477}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eb181f2c4bf2054016a547a48257c81919e552a1d520ee435"}},"id":"prt_f59fdaaf3001baoblKsQphUE2X","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f59fd3cf1001i0c3uxYZV1prra"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921224520,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_IfLJbFmR18MCrDg90rKAAFEM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/best_practices_and_summary.md","offset":1,"limit":130},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/best_practices_and_summary.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Best Practices, Library Summary & Related\n3: description: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns. — Best Practices, Library Summary & Related.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"best practices library\"\n6:   - \"practices library summary\"\n7:   - \"best practices patterns\"\n8:   - \"webflow best practices\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Best Practices, Library Summary & Related\n15: \n16: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns. — Best Practices, Library Summary & Related.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Cross-library best practices for third-party integrations, plus a summary of the supported libraries and what each one is for.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Choosing among the supported third-party libraries\n29: - Applying cross-library integration best practices (CDN loading, version pinning, error handling)\n30: - Looking up what a given library is for\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## 2. BEST PRACTICES\n35: \n36: ### CDN Loading Pattern\n37: \n38: ```javascript\n39: // ✅ Good: Version pinned, origin-allowlisted, async, error handled\n40: const CDN_URL = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@{version}';\n41: const ALLOWED_CDN_HOSTS = ['cdn.jsdelivr.net', 'unpkg.com'];\n42: \n43: async function load_with_timeout(url, timeout_ms = 10000) {\n44:   // Never inject an unvalidated URL as a script src — restrict to trusted CDN origins.\n45:   let parsed;\n46:   try { parsed = new URL(url); } catch { return false; }\n47:   if (parsed.protocol !== 'https:' || !ALLOWED_CDN_HOSTS.includes(parsed.hostname)) {\n48:     return false;\n49:   }\n50: \n51:   return new Promise((resolve) => {\n52:     const timer = setTimeout(() => resolve(false), timeout_ms);\n53: \n54:     const script = document.createElement('script');\n55:     script.src = parsed.href;\n56:     script.async = true;\n57:     // Add Subresource Integrity when the hash is known: script.integrity = 'sha384-…'; script.crossOrigin = 'anonymous';\n58:     script.onload = () => { clearTimeout(timer); resolve(true); };\n59:     script.onerror = () => { clearTimeout(timer); resolve(false); };\n60:     document.head.appendChild(script);\n61:   });\n62: }\n63: \n64: // ❌ Bad: No version, no error handling, unvalidated src\n65: document.write('<script src=\"https://cdn.example.com/lib.js\"></script>');\n66: ```\n67: \n68: ### Version Pinning\n69: \n70: ```javascript\n71: // ✅ Pinned to specific version (check HTML source for current versions)\n72: 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{major.minor.patch}'\n73: \n74: // ✅ Pinned to specific minor version\n75: 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@studio-freight/lenis@{major.minor}'\n76: \n77: // ❌ Avoid: Latest tag can break unexpectedly\n78: 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@latest'\n79: \n80: // ❌ Avoid: Unpinned versions\n81: 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library'\n82: ```\n83: \n84: ### Fallback Strategies\n85: \n86: ```javascript\n87: // Pattern: Retry loader for race conditions\n88: const MAX_RETRIES = 10;\n89: const RETRY_DELAY_MS = 120;\n90: let retry_count = 0;\n91: \n92: function init_with_library() {\n93:   if (typeof Library === 'undefined') {\n94:     if (++retry_count < MAX_RETRIES) {\n95:       console.warn(`Library not ready, retry ${retry_count}/${MAX_RETRIES}`);\n96:       setTimeout(init_with_library, RETRY_DELAY_MS);\n97:       return;\n98:     }\n99:     console.error('Library failed to load');\n100:     return;\n101:   }\n102:   \n103:   retry_count = 0;\n104:   // ... initialization code\n105: }\n106: ```\n107: \n108: ### Error Boundaries\n109: \n110: ```javascript\n111: // Wrap third-party calls in try-catch\n112: function safe_library_call(action) {\n113:   try {\n114:     return action();\n115:   } catch (error) {\n116:     console.warn('Library error:', error);\n117:     return null;\n118:   }\n119: }\n120: \n121: // Usage\n122: safe_library_call(() => {\n123:   window.lenis?.scrollTo(target);\n124: });\n125: ```\n126: \n127: ### Preload Critical Libraries\n128: \n129: ```html\n130: <!-- In <head> for critical path libraries -->\n\n(Showing lines 1-130 of 183. Use offset=131 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Best Practices, Library Summary & Related\ndescription: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns. — Best Practices, Library Summary & Related.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"best practices library\"\n  - \"practices library summary\"\n  - \"best practices patterns\"\n  - \"webflow best practices\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Best Practices, Library Summary & Related\n\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns. — Best Practices, Library Summary & Related.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/best_practices_and_summary.md","text":"---\ntitle: Best Practices, Library Summary & Related\ndescription: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns. — Best Practices, Library Summary & Related.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"best practices library\"\n  - \"practices library summary\"\n  - \"best practices patterns\"\n  - \"webflow best practices\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Best Practices, Library Summary & Related\n\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns. — Best Practices, Library Summary & Related.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nCross-library best practices for third-party integrations, plus a summary of the supported libraries and what each one is for.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Choosing among the supported third-party libraries\n- Applying cross-library integration best practices (CDN loading, version pinning, error handling)\n- Looking up what a given library is for\n\n---\n\n## 2. BEST PRACTICES\n\n### CDN Loading Pattern\n\n```javascript\n// ✅ Good: Version pinned, origin-allowlisted, async, error handled\nconst CDN_URL = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@{version}';\nconst ALLOWED_CDN_HOSTS = ['cdn.jsdelivr.net', 'unpkg.com'];\n\nasync function load_with_timeout(url, timeout_ms = 10000) {\n  // Never inject an unvalidated URL as a script src — restrict to trusted CDN origins.\n  let parsed;\n  try { parsed = new URL(url); } catch { return false; }\n  if (parsed.protocol !== 'https:' || !ALLOWED_CDN_HOSTS.includes(parsed.hostname)) {\n    return false;\n  }\n\n  return new Promise((resolve) => {\n    const timer = setTimeout(() => resolve(false), timeout_ms);\n\n    const script = document.createElement('script');\n    script.src = parsed.href;\n    script.async = true;\n    // Add Subresource Integrity when the hash is known: script.integrity = 'sha384-…'; script.crossOrigin = 'anonymous';\n    script.onload = () => { clearTimeout(timer); resolve(true); };\n    script.onerror = () => { clearTimeout(timer); resolve(false); };\n    document.head.appendChild(script);\n  });\n}\n\n// ❌ Bad: No version, no error handling, unvalidated src\ndocument.write('<script src=\"https://cdn.example.com/lib.js\"></script>');\n```\n\n### Version Pinning\n\n```javascript\n// ✅ Pinned to specific version (check HTML source for current versions)\n'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{major.minor.patch}'\n\n// ✅ Pinned to specific minor version\n'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@studio-freight/lenis@{major.minor}'\n\n// ❌ Avoid: Latest tag can break unexpectedly\n'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@latest'\n\n// ❌ Avoid: Unpinned versions\n'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library'\n```\n\n### Fallback Strategies\n\n```javascript\n// Pattern: Retry loader for race conditions\nconst MAX_RETRIES = 10;\nconst RETRY_DELAY_MS = 120;\nlet retry_count = 0;\n\nfunction init_with_library() {\n  if (typeof Library === 'undefined') {\n    if (++retry_count < MAX_RETRIES) {\n      console.warn(`Library not ready, retry ${retry_count}/${MAX_RETRIES}`);\n      setTimeout(init_with_library, RETRY_DELAY_MS);\n      return;\n    }\n    console.error('Library failed to load');\n    return;\n  }\n  \n  retry_count = 0;\n  // ... initialization code\n}\n```\n\n### Error Boundaries\n\n```javascript\n// Wrap third-party calls in try-catch\nfunction safe_library_call(action) {\n  try {\n    return action();\n  } catch (error) {\n    console.warn('Library error:', error);\n    return null;\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage\nsafe_library_call(() => {\n  window.lenis?.scrollTo(target);\n});\n```\n\n### Preload Critical Libraries\n\n```html\n<!-- In <head> for critical path libraries -->","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":130,"totalLines":183,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/best_practices_and_summary.md","time":{"start":1783921224509,"end":1783921224518}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eb181f2c4bf2054016a547a4825f88191a05555a2169c6003"}},"id":"prt_f59fdab13001NIGNngHg0Ijrth","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f59fd3cf1001i0c3uxYZV1prra"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921224606,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dYf2hO8SiUW2izm2kbsaZbPx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md","offset":1,"limit":70},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Workflow Reference - Debugging\n3: description: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for sk-code — root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure, consumed by every surface packet.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code debugging workflow\"\n6:   - \"debug workflow doctrine\"\n7:   - \"root-cause diagnosis\"\n8:   - \"scoped repair workflow\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.0.0.1\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Workflow Reference - Debugging\n15: \n16: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure appears. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Debugging is the controlled experiment phase. It reproduces or tightly characterizes the symptom, captures exact evidence, traces the symptom backward to a source cause, applies one-cause fixes, and sends the result back through quality and verification.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Diagnosing a failing test, build failure, runtime exception, console error, broken interaction, layout regression, command failure, or inconsistent runtime behavior.\n29: - Recovering from failed implementation, failed quality, failed verification, or a concrete regression.\n30: - Tracing a symptom backward before changing code.\n31: - Applying a minimal bug fix to already-scoped files after the root cause is identified.\n32: - Dispatching a bounded parallel investigation when the search space is broad but the symptom is concrete.\n33: - Enforcing the three-strike escalation rule after repeated failed fixes for the same symptom.\n34: \n35: ### When Not to Use\n36: \n37: - The work is planned implementation or refactoring without a failing symptom; use the implementation phase.\n38: - The work is an author-side quality gate with no concrete failing behavior; use the quality phase.\n39: - The work is final non-mutating evidence after a fix; use the verification phase.\n40: - The user wants findings-first review output rather than author-side repair.\n41: - The task is documentation-only prose with no failing behavior.\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## 2. WORKFLOW\n46: \n47: ### Debug Loop\n48: \n49: 1. Resolve the active surface and lifecycle phase through shared references. If the surface is unknown, ask for runtime and verification commands before changing code.\n50: 2. Reproduce the symptom. If it cannot be reproduced, collect the exact command, logs, inputs, state, or interaction steps needed to narrow it.\n51: 3. Capture evidence verbatim: command, exit code, stack trace, console output, failing assertion, path, viewport, input, or observed behavior.\n52: 4. Localize the fault by tracing backward from symptom to immediate cause to source cause.\n53: 5. State the current hypothesis and the evidence that would confirm or refute it.\n54: 6. Change one cause at a time, keeping the fix as small as the evidence supports.\n55: 7. Rerun the original reproduction step after every fix.\n56: 8. If the fix changes code, return through quality before final verification.\n57: 9. Hand the fixed state to verification with the reproduction command, before/after result, and residual risk.\n58: \n59: ### Four-Phase Checklist Substance\n60: \n61: Use the universal debugging checklist as the detailed walk-through, not as content to duplicate wholesale:\n62: \n63: | Phase | Required Discipline |\n64: | --- | --- |\n65: | Root Cause Investigation | Reproduce reliably, capture exact output, identify the failing layer, note last-known-good state, and inspect what changed. |\n66: | Pattern Analysis | Search exact error strings, separate symptom from cause, trace backward, and compare against similar past issues. |\n67: | Hypothesis Testing | State one hypothesis, predict confirming/refuting evidence, test one variable, and document the observed result. |\n68: | Fix | Fix at source, add or preserve regression coverage when appropriate, and rerun the original reproduction step. |\n69: \n70: ### One-Cause Fix Rule\n\n(Showing lines 1-70 of 121. Use offset=71 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Debugging\ndescription: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for sk-code — root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code debugging workflow\"\n  - \"debug workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"root-cause diagnosis\"\n  - \"scoped repair workflow\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.1\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Debugging\n\nShared debugging workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure appears. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md","text":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Debugging\ndescription: Shared debugging workflow doctrine for sk-code — root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code debugging workflow\"\n  - \"debug workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"root-cause diagnosis\"\n  - \"scoped repair workflow\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.1\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Debugging\n\nShared debugging workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers root-cause diagnosis and scoped repair after a symptom, failing command, runtime error, quality failure, or verification failure appears. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDebugging is the controlled experiment phase. It reproduces or tightly characterizes the symptom, captures exact evidence, traces the symptom backward to a source cause, applies one-cause fixes, and sends the result back through quality and verification.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Diagnosing a failing test, build failure, runtime exception, console error, broken interaction, layout regression, command failure, or inconsistent runtime behavior.\n- Recovering from failed implementation, failed quality, failed verification, or a concrete regression.\n- Tracing a symptom backward before changing code.\n- Applying a minimal bug fix to already-scoped files after the root cause is identified.\n- Dispatching a bounded parallel investigation when the search space is broad but the symptom is concrete.\n- Enforcing the three-strike escalation rule after repeated failed fixes for the same symptom.\n\n### When Not to Use\n\n- The work is planned implementation or refactoring without a failing symptom; use the implementation phase.\n- The work is an author-side quality gate with no concrete failing behavior; use the quality phase.\n- The work is final non-mutating evidence after a fix; use the verification phase.\n- The user wants findings-first review output rather than author-side repair.\n- The task is documentation-only prose with no failing behavior.\n\n---\n\n## 2. WORKFLOW\n\n### Debug Loop\n\n1. Resolve the active surface and lifecycle phase through shared references. If the surface is unknown, ask for runtime and verification commands before changing code.\n2. Reproduce the symptom. If it cannot be reproduced, collect the exact command, logs, inputs, state, or interaction steps needed to narrow it.\n3. Capture evidence verbatim: command, exit code, stack trace, console output, failing assertion, path, viewport, input, or observed behavior.\n4. Localize the fault by tracing backward from symptom to immediate cause to source cause.\n5. State the current hypothesis and the evidence that would confirm or refute it.\n6. Change one cause at a time, keeping the fix as small as the evidence supports.\n7. Rerun the original reproduction step after every fix.\n8. If the fix changes code, return through quality before final verification.\n9. Hand the fixed state to verification with the reproduction command, before/after result, and residual risk.\n\n### Four-Phase Checklist Substance\n\nUse the universal debugging checklist as the detailed walk-through, not as content to duplicate wholesale:\n\n| Phase | Required Discipline |\n| --- | --- |\n| Root Cause Investigation | Reproduce reliably, capture exact output, identify the failing layer, note last-known-good state, and inspect what changed. |\n| Pattern Analysis | Search exact error strings, separate symptom from cause, trace backward, and compare against similar past issues. |\n| Hypothesis Testing | State one hypothesis, predict confirming/refuting evidence, test one variable, and document the observed result. |\n| Fix | Fix at source, add or preserve regression coverage when appropriate, and rerun the original reproduction step. |\n\n### One-Cause Fix Rule","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":70,"totalLines":121,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_debug.md","time":{"start":1783921224595,"end":1783921224605}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eb181f2c4bf2054016a547a4826048191af84d9df41bab146"}},"id":"prt_f59fdab42001bKjLlTDSGq6sae","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f59fd3cf1001i0c3uxYZV1prra"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921224627,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_VH7ENExSWJYdkzHCspWonZQX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md","offset":1,"limit":60},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow CSS Quality Standards\"\n3: description: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow css quality standards\"\n6:   - \"will change management\"\n7:   - \"gpu accelerated properties\"\n8:   - \"css custom property prefix\"\n9:   - \"bem naming enforcement\"\n10:   - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n11:   - \"fluid typography webflow\"\n12: importance_tier: normal\n13: contextType: implementation\n14: version: 3.5.0.2\n15: ---\n16: \n17: # Webflow CSS Quality Standards\n18: \n19: > See [`../style_guide.md`](../style_guide.md) for CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, and file organization. See [`../../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for cross-language rules. This file covers CSS quality patterns AND CSS-specific enforcement.\n20: \n21: ---\n22: \n23: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n24: \n25: ### Purpose\n26: \n27: CSS quality patterns (will-change management, GPU acceleration, easing standards, fluid typography) plus the four CSS-specific enforcement subsections (custom property naming, attribute selector i flag, BEM, animation properties).\n28: \n29: ### When to Use\n30: \n31: - Validating CSS before claiming implementation complete\n32: - Fixing CSS violations identified by the code quality checklist\n33: - Setting up will-change cleanup or fluid-typography breakpoints\n34: \n35: ### Core Principle\n36: \n37: Defensive CSS patterns prevent runtime jank; explicit enforcement rules prevent silent regressions.\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## 2. CSS QUALITY PATTERNS\n42: \n43: ### will-change Management\n44: \n45: ```css\n46: /* Set will-change in JavaScript BEFORE animation starts */\n47: .animating {\n48:   will-change: transform, opacity;\n49: }\n50: \n51: /* Reset after animation completes (via JavaScript) */\n52: .animation-complete {\n53:   will-change: auto;\n54: }\n55: ```\n56: \n57: ### GPU-Accelerated Properties Only\n58: \n59: ```css\n60: .animated-element {\n\n(Showing lines 1-60 of 307. Use offset=61 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Quality Standards\"\ndescription: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css quality standards\"\n  - \"will change management\"\n  - \"gpu accelerated properties\"\n  - \"css custom property prefix\"\n  - \"bem naming enforcement\"\n  - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n  - \"fluid typography webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Quality Standards\n\n> See [`../style_guide.md`](../style_guide.md) for CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, and file organization. See [`../../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for cross-language rules. This file covers CSS quality patterns AND CSS-specific enforcement.\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow CSS Quality Standards\"\ndescription: \"CSS quality patterns for Webflow: will-change management (set in JS, cleanup after), GPU-accelerated properties (transform/opacity only), Motion.dev-aligned easing, fluid typography. Includes CSS enforcement: custom property naming (--font-/--vw-/--component-/--state-/--global-), attribute selector case-insensitivity (i flag), BEM naming, animation property restrictions.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css quality standards\"\n  - \"will change management\"\n  - \"gpu accelerated properties\"\n  - \"css custom property prefix\"\n  - \"bem naming enforcement\"\n  - \"css attribute selector flag\"\n  - \"fluid typography webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow CSS Quality Standards\n\n> See [`../style_guide.md`](../style_guide.md) for CSS naming, custom property prefixes, attribute selectors, animation CSS, and file organization. See [`../../shared/cross_language_rules.md`](../../shared/cross_language_rules.md) for cross-language rules. This file covers CSS quality patterns AND CSS-specific enforcement.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nCSS quality patterns (will-change management, GPU acceleration, easing standards, fluid typography) plus the four CSS-specific enforcement subsections (custom property naming, attribute selector i flag, BEM, animation properties).\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Validating CSS before claiming implementation complete\n- Fixing CSS violations identified by the code quality checklist\n- Setting up will-change cleanup or fluid-typography breakpoints\n\n### Core Principle\n\nDefensive CSS patterns prevent runtime jank; explicit enforcement rules prevent silent regressions.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CSS QUALITY PATTERNS\n\n### will-change Management\n\n```css\n/* Set will-change in JavaScript BEFORE animation starts */\n.animating {\n  will-change: transform, opacity;\n}\n\n/* Reset after animation completes (via JavaScript) */\n.animation-complete {\n  will-change: auto;\n}\n```\n\n### GPU-Accelerated Properties Only\n\n```css\n.animated-element {","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":60,"totalLines":307,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md","time":{"start":1783921224618,"end":1783921224626}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0eb181f2c4bf2054016a547a48260c8191ad9eae7f73b90067"}},"id":"prt_f59fdab95001V6YbJnLNt7X9JE","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f59fd3cf1001i0c3uxYZV1prra"}}
