{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921405545,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_fFOa0WMpqGC7281sBzPUdRPM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/shared/enforcement.md","offset":1,"limit":90},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/shared/enforcement.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Webflow Code Style Enforcement: Cross-Language Workflow\"\n3: description: \"Enforcement workflow, validation prompts, and remediation guidance for cross-language style rules (file headers, section organization, comment quality). Per-language enforcement (JS naming, JS init patterns, CSS BEM, CSS attribute selectors, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language quality_standards.md.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow style enforcement\"\n6:   - \"code style enforcement gate\"\n7:   - \"pre completion gate\"\n8:   - \"p0 p1 p2 violations\"\n9:   - \"validation prompts remediation\"\n10: importance_tier: important\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 3.5.0.2\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Webflow Code Style Enforcement: Cross-Language Workflow\n16: \n17: This file enforces rules that apply to all Webflow languages (JavaScript and CSS). Per-language enforcement (JS naming conventions, JS initialization patterns, CSS custom properties, CSS attribute selectors, CSS BEM, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language `quality_standards.md`.\n18: \n19: **Related Documents:**\n20: - [`../javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md`](../javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md) — JS style conventions (naming, file structure, formatting, JSDoc)\n21: - [`../css/style_guide.md`](../css/style_guide.md) — CSS style conventions (BEM, custom properties, attribute selectors, animation CSS)\n22: - [`../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md`](../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) — JS quality patterns + JS naming/init enforcement\n23: - [`../css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](../css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) — CSS quality patterns + 4 CSS enforcement subsections\n24: - [`../../../assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`](../../../code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md) — validation checklist used at the pre-completion gate\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n29: \n30: ### Purpose\n31: \n32: This document provides:\n33: - Validation prompts for checking code compliance\n34: - Pattern recognition guidance for identifying violations\n35: - Compliant and non-compliant examples for comparison\n36: - Remediation instructions for fixing common violations\n37: \n38: ### When to Use\n39: \n40: Use this enforcement reference when:\n41: - Validating **JavaScript or CSS** code before claiming implementation complete\n42: - Fixing violations identified by the code quality checklist\n43: - Understanding the difference between compliant and non-compliant patterns\n44: - Training on code style standards\n45: \n46: ### Enforcement Philosophy\n47: \n48: - **P0 violations** are HARD BLOCKERS - must be fixed before completion\n49: - **P1 violations** should be fixed OR documented with approval\n50: - **P2 violations** can be deferred with documented reason\n51: - When in doubt, fix the violation rather than defer\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## 2. FILE HEADER ENFORCEMENT\n56: \n57: ### Validation Prompt\n58: \n59: > **Check:** Does the file start with a three-line header using box-drawing characters?\n60: \n61: **What to look for:**\n62: 1. First line: `// ─` followed by 63 more `─` characters (67 total including `// `)\n63: 2. Second line: `// CATEGORY: COMPONENT NAME` (ALL CAPS)\n64: 3. Third line: Same as first line\n65: \n66: ### Pattern Recognition\n67: \n68: **Compliant Pattern:**\n69: ```javascript\n70: // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n71: // VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER\n72: // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n73: ```\n74: \n75: **Violation Patterns:**\n76: \n77: | Violation        | Example                 | How to Identify                 |\n78: | ---------------- | ----------------------- | ------------------------------- |\n79: | Missing header   | File starts with code   | No header lines at top          |\n80: | Wrong character  | `// ---...`             | Uses hyphen `-` instead of `─`  |\n81: | Wrong length     | Short header line       | Count characters (should be 67) |\n82: | Metadata present | `// Created 2024-01-15` | Contains dates, names, versions |\n83: | Wrong case       | `// video: Background`  | Not ALL CAPS                    |\n84: \n85: ### Remediation\n86: \n87: **To fix missing header:**\n88: 1. Insert three lines at the top of the file\n89: 2. Copy the template:\n90: ```javascript\n\n(Showing lines 1-90 of 328. Use offset=91 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow Code Style Enforcement: Cross-Language Workflow\"\ndescription: \"Enforcement workflow, validation prompts, and remediation guidance for cross-language style rules (file headers, section organization, comment quality). Per-language enforcement (JS naming, JS init patterns, CSS BEM, CSS attribute selectors, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language quality_standards.md.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow style enforcement\"\n  - \"code style enforcement gate\"\n  - \"pre completion gate\"\n  - \"p0 p1 p2 violations\"\n  - \"validation prompts remediation\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow Code Style Enforcement: Cross-Language Workflow\n\nThis file enforces rules that apply to all Webflow languages (JavaScript and CSS). Per-language enforcement (JS naming conventions, JS initialization patterns, CSS custom properties, CSS attribute selectors, CSS BEM, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language `quality_standards.md`.\n\n**Related Documents:**\n- [`../javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md`](../javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md) — JS style conventions (naming, file structure, formatting, JSDoc)","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/shared/enforcement.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Webflow Code Style Enforcement: Cross-Language Workflow\"\ndescription: \"Enforcement workflow, validation prompts, and remediation guidance for cross-language style rules (file headers, section organization, comment quality). Per-language enforcement (JS naming, JS init patterns, CSS BEM, CSS attribute selectors, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language quality_standards.md.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow style enforcement\"\n  - \"code style enforcement gate\"\n  - \"pre completion gate\"\n  - \"p0 p1 p2 violations\"\n  - \"validation prompts remediation\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.2\n---\n\n# Webflow Code Style Enforcement: Cross-Language Workflow\n\nThis file enforces rules that apply to all Webflow languages (JavaScript and CSS). Per-language enforcement (JS naming conventions, JS initialization patterns, CSS custom properties, CSS attribute selectors, CSS BEM, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language `quality_standards.md`.\n\n**Related Documents:**\n- [`../javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md`](../javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md) — JS style conventions (naming, file structure, formatting, JSDoc)\n- [`../css/style_guide.md`](../css/style_guide.md) — CSS style conventions (BEM, custom properties, attribute selectors, animation CSS)\n- [`../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md`](../javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) — JS quality patterns + JS naming/init enforcement\n- [`../css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md`](../css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) — CSS quality patterns + 4 CSS enforcement subsections\n- [`../../../assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`](../../../code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md) — validation checklist used at the pre-completion gate\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis document provides:\n- Validation prompts for checking code compliance\n- Pattern recognition guidance for identifying violations\n- Compliant and non-compliant examples for comparison\n- Remediation instructions for fixing common violations\n\n### When to Use\n\nUse this enforcement reference when:\n- Validating **JavaScript or CSS** code before claiming implementation complete\n- Fixing violations identified by the code quality checklist\n- Understanding the difference between compliant and non-compliant patterns\n- Training on code style standards\n\n### Enforcement Philosophy\n\n- **P0 violations** are HARD BLOCKERS - must be fixed before completion\n- **P1 violations** should be fixed OR documented with approval\n- **P2 violations** can be deferred with documented reason\n- When in doubt, fix the violation rather than defer\n\n---\n\n## 2. FILE HEADER ENFORCEMENT\n\n### Validation Prompt\n\n> **Check:** Does the file start with a three-line header using box-drawing characters?\n\n**What to look for:**\n1. First line: `// ─` followed by 63 more `─` characters (67 total including `// `)\n2. Second line: `// CATEGORY: COMPONENT NAME` (ALL CAPS)\n3. Third line: Same as first line\n\n### Pattern Recognition\n\n**Compliant Pattern:**\n```javascript\n// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER\n// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n```\n\n**Violation Patterns:**\n\n| Violation        | Example                 | How to Identify                 |\n| ---------------- | ----------------------- | ------------------------------- |\n| Missing header   | File starts with code   | No header lines at top          |\n| Wrong character  | `// ---...`             | Uses hyphen `-` instead of `─`  |\n| Wrong length     | Short header line       | Count characters (should be 67) |\n| Metadata present | `// Created 2024-01-15` | Contains dates, names, versions |\n| Wrong case       | `// video: Background`  | Not ALL CAPS                    |\n\n### Remediation\n\n**To fix missing header:**\n1. Insert three lines at the top of the file\n2. Copy the template:\n```javascript","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":90,"totalLines":328,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/shared/enforcement.md","time":{"start":1783921405539,"end":1783921405544}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_012044b5f6fa9f27016a547afd709481918ee542ffc12650da"}},"id":"prt_f5a006e2c001OpuUHGpmj42yav","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f5a00358f001WnWr16gk28dPGC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921405594,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_UyOTmdmfccWhbxWtIB9S1Pj9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md","offset":1,"limit":38},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Workflow Reference - Implementation\n3: description: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for sk-code — research and mutating build work run after the shared router resolves the active surface, consumed by every surface packet.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code implementation workflow\"\n6:   - \"implement workflow doctrine\"\n7:   - \"mutating build workflow\"\n8:   - \"surface implementation standards\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 4.1.0.2\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Workflow Reference - Implementation\n15: \n16: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers research and mutating build work after the shared router has resolved the active surface. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Implementation is the mutating build phase. It owns research before change, the smallest correct workspace edit, and the handoff into quality, debugging, and verification. It consumes surface identity from the shared router and then loads only the active surface resources needed for the task.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Writing, modifying, refactoring, or building code in the active surface.\n29: - Implementing a feature, script, component, module, fallback, parameter, authoring packet, or runtime behavior.\n30: - Researching unfamiliar, risky, config-sensitive, security-sensitive, or multi-file code before changing it.\n31: - Applying surface-specific authoring patterns after the active surface has already been resolved.\n32: - Consuming an animation or motion overlay as peer reference material after surface detection, not as a replacement for surface standards.\n33: \n34: ### When Not to Use\n35: \n36: - A concrete failing symptom is the dominant task; switch to debugging.\n37: - The implementation is already written and needs author-side P0/P1/P2 checks, comment hygiene, or surface checklists; proceed to quality.\n38: - The task is final non-mutating evidence; proceed to verification.\n\n(Showing lines 1-38 of 125. Use offset=39 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Implementation\ndescription: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for sk-code — research and mutating build work run after the shared router resolves the active surface, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code implementation workflow\"\n  - \"implement workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"mutating build workflow\"\n  - \"surface implementation standards\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Implementation\n\nShared implementation workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers research and mutating build work after the shared router has resolved the active surface. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md","text":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Implementation\ndescription: Shared implementation workflow doctrine for sk-code — research and mutating build work run after the shared router resolves the active surface, consumed by every surface packet.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code implementation workflow\"\n  - \"implement workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"mutating build workflow\"\n  - \"surface implementation standards\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Implementation\n\nShared implementation workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers research and mutating build work after the shared router has resolved the active surface. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nImplementation is the mutating build phase. It owns research before change, the smallest correct workspace edit, and the handoff into quality, debugging, and verification. It consumes surface identity from the shared router and then loads only the active surface resources needed for the task.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Writing, modifying, refactoring, or building code in the active surface.\n- Implementing a feature, script, component, module, fallback, parameter, authoring packet, or runtime behavior.\n- Researching unfamiliar, risky, config-sensitive, security-sensitive, or multi-file code before changing it.\n- Applying surface-specific authoring patterns after the active surface has already been resolved.\n- Consuming an animation or motion overlay as peer reference material after surface detection, not as a replacement for surface standards.\n\n### When Not to Use\n\n- A concrete failing symptom is the dominant task; switch to debugging.\n- The implementation is already written and needs author-side P0/P1/P2 checks, comment hygiene, or surface checklists; proceed to quality.\n- The task is final non-mutating evidence; proceed to verification.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":38,"totalLines":125,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_implement.md","time":{"start":1783921405589,"end":1783921405593}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_012044b5f6fa9f27016a547afd70b8819199eb7e893ca69ac5"}},"id":"prt_f5a006e65001Bs3xA6ApMURMAS","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f5a00358f001WnWr16gk28dPGC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921405616,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_P5bLqyrhaUp0mvGgaQFkG8lE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md","offset":1,"limit":38},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Workflow Reference - Verification\n3: description: Shared verification workflow doctrine for sk-code — the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done/works/complete/fixed/passing/ready claim.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code verification workflow\"\n6:   - \"verify workflow doctrine\"\n7:   - \"falsifier discipline\"\n8:   - \"completion claim gate\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 4.1.0.2\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Workflow Reference - Verification\n15: \n16: Shared verification workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Verification owns evidence, not fixes. It runs fresh surface-appropriate commands, records outcomes, compares against the implementation baseline, names blind spots, and claims only what the evidence proves. If verification fails, it hands back to debugging, implementation, or quality without editing.\n25: \n26: ### Iron Law\n27: \n28: **Iron Law** — make no completion claim without fresh surface-appropriate verification evidence. A clean static read is not runtime evidence, a green unit test is not live proof, a minified bundle is not browser interaction, and a browser click is not full regression coverage; name the rung and its blind spot.\n29: \n30: ### When to Use\n31: \n32: - Verifying work after implementation, quality checks, or debugging.\n33: - Running final commands before a done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim.\n34: - Collecting evidence for active-surface behavior or system-code changes.\n35: - Reporting the delta from the baseline captured before implementation.\n36: - Running mutation checks or claim-falsifier checks after a green result.\n37: - Walking the verification ladder and naming each rung's blind spot.\n38: \n\n(Showing lines 1-38 of 175. Use offset=39 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Verification\ndescription: Shared verification workflow doctrine for sk-code — the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done/works/complete/fixed/passing/ready claim.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code verification workflow\"\n  - \"verify workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"falsifier discipline\"\n  - \"completion claim gate\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Verification\n\nShared verification workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md","text":"---\ntitle: Workflow Reference - Verification\ndescription: Shared verification workflow doctrine for sk-code — the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done/works/complete/fixed/passing/ready claim.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code verification workflow\"\n  - \"verify workflow doctrine\"\n  - \"falsifier discipline\"\n  - \"completion claim gate\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: general\nversion: 4.1.0.2\n---\n\n# Workflow Reference - Verification\n\nShared verification workflow doctrine for `sk-code`. This reference covers the non-mutating evidence phase that runs last, compares against baseline, applies falsifier discipline, and gates any done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim. It is consumed by surface packets and defines no skill identity or surface-specific standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nVerification owns evidence, not fixes. It runs fresh surface-appropriate commands, records outcomes, compares against the implementation baseline, names blind spots, and claims only what the evidence proves. If verification fails, it hands back to debugging, implementation, or quality without editing.\n\n### Iron Law\n\n**Iron Law** — make no completion claim without fresh surface-appropriate verification evidence. A clean static read is not runtime evidence, a green unit test is not live proof, a minified bundle is not browser interaction, and a browser click is not full regression coverage; name the rung and its blind spot.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Verifying work after implementation, quality checks, or debugging.\n- Running final commands before a done, works, complete, fixed, passing, or ready claim.\n- Collecting evidence for active-surface behavior or system-code changes.\n- Reporting the delta from the baseline captured before implementation.\n- Running mutation checks or claim-falsifier checks after a green result.\n- Walking the verification ladder and naming each rung's blind spot.\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":38,"totalLines":175,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/workflow_verify.md","time":{"start":1783921405613,"end":1783921405615}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_012044b5f6fa9f27016a547afd70c081918017f4518f5dd45d"}},"id":"prt_f5a006e97001k72onsIlHpnE7b","sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","messageID":"msg_f5a00358f001WnWr16gk28dPGC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783921405677,"sessionID":"ses_0a60505fdffeqSdEmZI11c4h43","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_0BLfwvtY9uIvtdcqpIdWQ54k","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"This file enforces rules that apply|Related Documents","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 5 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:\n  Line 72: The Phase 3 bulk sed pass missed six references in `webflow/shared/enforcement.md` because the sweep regex did not match the bare-filename references like `[code_quality_standards.md](code_quality_standards.md)` (no path prefix). This release replaces all six with the correct per-language tree paths and rewrites the surrounding \"Related Documents\" block as a five-link tree map.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/README.md:\n  Line 127: ### Related Documents\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/shared/enforcement.md:\n  Line 17: This file enforces rules that apply to all Webflow languages (JavaScript and CSS). Per-language enforcement (JS naming conventions, JS initialization patterns, CSS custom properties, CSS attribute selectors, CSS BEM, CSS animation properties) lives in the matching language `quality_standards.md`.\n\n  Line 19: **Related Documents:**\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/shared/universal_patterns/organization_security_and_examples.md:\n  Line 308: ### Related Documents\n","metadata":{"matches":5,"truncated":false},"title":"This file enforces rules that apply|Related Documents","time":{"start":1783921405639,"end":1783921405672}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_012044b5f6fa9f